{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:54:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:54:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18926"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18926"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.01,0.29,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11659"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11367"},{"type":"tags","id":"11371"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27435"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA major incident occurs at a chemical plant, resulting in multiple casualties arriving simultaneously at a small regional emergency department. Many patients are experiencing respiratory distress and chemical burns. The department has limited staff and ventilators, though adequate personal protective equipment is available.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most appropriate initial ethical response in this emergency situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Treat patients in order of arrival time","Provide equal treatment time to each patient","Evacuate the emergency department","Focus resources on the most severely injured","Prioritise treatment based on survival probability"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprioritise treatment based on survival probability\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach aligns with established emergency triage principles and maximises benefit for the greatest number of patients while making optimal use of limited resources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreat patients in order of arrival time\u003C/strong\u003E - This first-come-first-served approach fails to consider medical urgency or resource optimisation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide equal treatment time to each patient\u003C/strong\u003E - This approach ignores differences in clinical need and would result in inefficient resource allocation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocus resources on the most severely injured\u003C/strong\u003E - This may consume excessive resources for potentially poor outcomes, reducing overall survival rates\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvacuate the emergency department\u003C/strong\u003E - This extreme response would abandon the duty of care without justification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring mass casualty incidents, ethical decision-making must balance individual patient needs against overall public benefit. This requires structured triage protocols that consider both survival probability and resource utilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The principle of justice requires fair allocation of limited healthcare resources during emergencies.","Triage protocols during emergencies prioritise doing the greatest good for the greatest number of people.","Healthcare workers have a duty of care but also a right to reasonable personal safety during emergencies."],"references":["Iserson KV. Ethical principles--emergency medicine. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2006 Aug;24(3):513-45. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2006.05.007. PMID: 16877128; PMCID: PMC7127201. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7127201/","Australian Medical Association. Ethical Considerations for Medical Practitioners in Disaster Response in Australia. [online]. 2022. [Cited 19 Jan 2025]. Available at: https://www.ama.com.au/sites/default/files/2022-11/Position%20Statement%20on%20Ethical%20Considerations%20for%20Medical%20Practitioners%20in%20Disaster%20Response%20in%20Australia%202022.pdf","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 18]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18926"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76174"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T14:07:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T14:39:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11659"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"